<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Chicken Note</div>
<div class="nbunit" id="edn3">  3  Many of the words used in the text in this war passage derive from a study of vocabulary in Rabelais. Most are the names of ancient implements of war: <i>badelaire</i>, <i>partisan</i>, <i>migraine</i>, <i>malchu</i>s, <i>verdun</i>, <i>baliste</i>, <i>aze gaye</i>, and so on. See in this connection Claude Jacquet, <i>Joyce et Rabelais: aspects de la creation verbale dans</i> Finnegans Wake (Paris, 1972), and Danis Rose, &lsquo;Corrections to Jacquet's Joyce et Rabelais&rsquo; (<i>A Wake Newslitter</i> [hereinafter abbreviated <i>AWN</i>] 13 (1976) pp 106-08 and 17 (1980) p 24). Joyce conflates flood, fall (from the wall, from Eden, and falling asleep), and first thunder.  </div>
